<HEADLINE>
<P>
BASEBALL / DAILY REPORT; AROUND THE MAJOR LEAGUES; PENA INJURES ELBOW AND GETS 
RELEASED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Alejandro Pena, emerging only a week ago as the Pittsburgh Pirates' first 
reliable closer in years, was given his outright release after reinjuring his 
surgically repaired right elbow. 
</P>
<P>
 Pena, 35, complained Tuesday in Chicago of elbow pain and returned to 
Pittsburgh to be examined by team orthopedist Jack Failla. General Manager Cam 
Bonifay released Pena after learning he might not return for weeks, if at all 
this season. 
</P>
<P>
 The right-handed reliever, who missed the 1993 season after requiring the 
surgery, cost the Pirates $1.475 million over two years for only 22 
appearances, all of them this season. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't know if he could make it back. It would be at least five weeks before 
he would be ready for rehabilitation, and maybe a lot longer," Bonifay said. 
"It was a tough decision but it was the right decision." 
</P>
<P>
 Activated May 1, Pena (3-2, 5.02 earned-run average) had seven saves in eight 
opportunities and was looking to become the Pirates' best closer since Jim Gott 
had a club-record 36 saves in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
 "The sad part is he was doing a hell of a job," Pirate Manager Jim Leyland 
said. "But you can't say it was unexpected, because we've been holding our 
breath since day one. It's been a crap shoot all the way along with him. But 
it's definitely a tough blow to lose your closer." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 San Francisco Giant center fielder Darren Lewis committed the first error of 
his career Thursday night, ending a major league record 392-game streak. 
</P>
<P>
 Lewis was given an error in the third inning when a base hit by Montreal's 
Cliff Floyd skipped under his glove as he charged the ball in shallow center. 
The error allowed Floyd to reach second. 
</P>
<P>
 Before the error, Lewis had handled 938 chances without a mistake. His streak 
was the longest ever without an error in the majors and the longest to start a 
career. 
</P>
<P>
 Lewis' last error came on May 10, 1991, at triple-A Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Paul Runge, making his third All-Star appearance, will be the home plate 
umpire for the July 12 All-Star Game at Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
 The commissioner's office said that Runge will be joined by fellow National 
Leaguers Jerry Layne at second base and Bill Hohn in left field, and American 
League umpires Jim Joyce in right field, Rocky Roe at third base and John 
Shulock at first. 
</P>
</TEXT>
