<HEADLINE>
<P>
VALLEYWIDE FOCUS: DESPERATELY SEEKING A GIG AS MADONNA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By VIVIEN LOU CHEN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Many swore they've never been Madonna wanna-bes. 
</P>
<P>
 But about 250 hopefuls dressed like the sensational, foul-mouthed pop singer 
waited in line outside a Burbank casting agency Thursday for the opportunity of 
a lifetime: playing Madonna in a two-hour television movie about her early 
career. 
</P>
<P>
 Several television and newspaper reporters were on hand, giving the aspiring 
actresses a taste of what being a celebrity is all about at the open casting 
call. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're not used to all this media, but I'm getting used to it," said Andrea 
Schurgin, 24, of Burbank, who brought her own microphone and a pair of backup 
singers, Naomi and Alyssa. 
</P>
<P>
 The three friends spent $50 for matching stockings, hair ribbons and rubber 
bracelets like the ones Madonna wore in her "Lucky Star" video. They practiced 
lip-syncing and twirling for three hours in front of a living room mirror 
Wednesday night. Others, such as Denise Vlasis of Sherman Oaks, came with 
considerably more experience. She's a professional Madonna impersonator earning 
upwards of $200 an hour. 
</P>
<P>
 Inside the Katy & Co. casting agency, the hopefuls performed 30-second dance 
routines and read from a script in front of a casting director and producers of 
"Madonna: The Early Years." 
</P>
<P>
 The film is set to begin shooting this month and will air on the Fox network 
in the fall. It chronicles Madonna Ciccone's life as a struggling artist in 
1978 to the success of her "Like a Virgin" album in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
 "It opens with a girl from Detroit who came to New York with $37 and was so 
broke she was eating out of garbage cans and squatting in abandoned buildings," 
said Michael Murray, the movie's scriptwriter. 
</P>
<P>
 "The early part of her career is the least examined and, in some ways, the 
most interesting. She was a street urchin who turned herself into a superstar." 
</P>
<P>
 "Acting is the most essential thing because it's a two-hour movie," said 
casting director Katy Wallin. "Even if Madonna isn't the best actress, we 
obviously want to cast someone who is qualified." VIVIEN LOU CHEN 
</P>
</TEXT>
